1) Load the files in several dataframes and remove the commas as delimiter for thousands¶

In [2]:
# For each file load the data and save them in to data frames
filein0 = "data/american_airline_empl.txt"
data0 = read.delim2(filein0, header = T, sep = "\t", col.names = c("Month", "Year", "Full.time.0", "Part.time.0", "Grand.Total.0"), dec=".")
# For each file take the commas off, in order to work with proper numbers and not strings
data0$Full.time.0 = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data0$Full.time.0))
data0$Part.time.0 = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data0$Part.time.0))
data0$Grand.Total.0 = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data0$Grand.Total.0))

filein1 = "data/delta_airline_empl.txt"
data1 = read.delim2(filein1, header = T, sep = "\t", col.names = c("Month", "Year", "Full.time.1", "Part.time.1", "Grand.Total.1"), dec=".")
data1$Full.time.1 = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", data1$Full.time.1))

# In order to give R the correct data format for the date, I change the month data
for (i in 1:length(data_total[,"Month"])) {
    month = "NA"
    if (data_total[i,"Month"] < 10) {
        month = paste0("0", as.character(data_total[i,"Month"]))
    } else {
        month = as.character(data_total[i,"Month"])
    }
    string_date = paste0(as.character(data_total[i,"Year"]), "-", month, "-01")

    # Create then the date column
    data_total[i,"data"] = as.Date.character((string_date), "%Y-%m-%d")
}

# The four labels are list("American Airline", "Delta Airline", "Federal Express", "United Airline")

4) Time when each company reaches the minimum and maximum number of employess¶

In [6]:
# Define the maxumim and minimum for each column
maximum = double(length(data_total)-3)
minimum = double(length(data_total)-3)

# Find the element of each column that satisfy the requirement for maximum:
for (i in 1:(length(data_total)-3)) {
    index = which.max(as.vector(unlist(data_total[i+2])))
    maximum[i] = data_total["data"][[1]][index]
}

# and for mimimum:
for (i in 1:(length(data_total)-3)) {
    index = which.min(as.vector(unlist(data_total[i+2])))
    minimum[i] = data_total["data"][[1]][index]
}

6) Did the COVID-19 pandemic have any influence in the employed workers of the airline companies? Can you see a trend in the years 2019-2023 ?¶

Two years before the pandemic there has been an increase in the number of Full-time employees. After that, there has been a consistent decrease in the total number of employees in 2021, for all the companies except Federal Express. The ratio of Part-time employees over the total number has kept a constant number of employees, except for Delta Airline.

Exercise 2: Data Frames and Tibble¶

The nycflights13 R package contains data on all flights departing from New Your City airports in 2013. All available data is organized into four tibbles:

  • airlines: contains metadata on airlines names and corresponding carrier codes
  • airports: contains metadata on all airports connected to NYC
  • flights: has data of all flights departing from the three NYC airports (JFK, LGA and EWR) in

2013

  • planes: Plane metadata for all plane numbers found in the FAA aircraft registry

# Create a new column showing the date in the wanted pattern
flights$data = as.Date(as.character(paste0(flights$year, "-", flights$month, "-", flights$day)))
# Group the flights per day and sum them
flights_per_day = flights %>% group_by(data, origin) %>% summarize(n = n())

# Divide the total number of flights per departure 
ewr = flights_per_day[flights_per_day$origin == "EWR",]
jfk = flights_per_day[flights_per_day$origin == "JFK",]
lga = flights_per_day[flights_per_day$origin == "LGA",]

# Plot using ggplot
ggplot(ewr, aes(data)) + 
    geom_point(aes(y = ewr$n), colour = "red") + 
    geom_point(aes(y = jfk$n), colour = "blue") + 
    geom_point(aes(y = lga$n), colour = "black") + 
    labs(title="Total number of flights per aeroport per day") +
    xlab("Increasing date") +
    ylab("Number of daily flights")

# Attach to every 
flights$weekday = weekdays(flights$data)

# Declare all the days we are interested in
working_days = c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday")
# Group by the day and sum all the flights per day
flights_per_working_week = flights %>% group_by(origin, week, weekday) %>% summarize(number = n())
# Select only data of the working days
flights_per_working_week = flights_per_working_week[flights_per_working_week$weekday %in% working_days,]
# Takes the average number of flights per week of the working day
flights_per_working_week = flights_per_working_week %>% group_by(origin, week) %>% summarise(mean_flights = mean(number), .groups="drop")


erw_working_week = flights_per_working_week[flights_per_working_week$origin == "EWR",]

# Plot using ggplot

In [13]:
# The departure delay is yet given in the "dep_delay" column
# Remove the lines that have a "NA" in the delay column (probably canceled flights) and then group by the data and origin and mean by the delay
mean_delays = flights[!is.na(flights$dep_delay),] %>% group_by(data, origin) %>% summarise(mean_delay = mean(dep_delay))
max_delays  = flights[!is.na(flights$dep_delay),] %>% group_by(data, origin) %>% summarise(mean_delay =  max(dep_delay))
min_delays  = flights[!is.na(flights$dep_delay),] %>% group_by(data, origin) %>% summarise(mean_delay =  min(dep_delay))

# Then we can plot the behaviour of these delays for each airport with ggplot
gg1 = ggplot(mean_delays[mean_delays$origin == "EWR",], aes(data)) + 
    geom_point(aes(y = mean_delays[mean_delays$origin == "EWR",]$mean_delay), colour = "red") +

2.5) Analyze the flights offered by each airline company and determine:¶

  • the airline companies offering the largest two numbers of flights per day and per week;¶

In [15]:
# Divide the flights per day and per company (carrier column corresponds to the IATA Code of the Federal Aviation Administration)
# Then order them per date and descending number of flights per company, selecting the top two (slice)
airline_largest = flights %>% group_by(data, carrier) %>% summarise(sum = n()) %>% arrange(data, desc(sum)) %>% slice(1:2)

# Now we have to FACTOR in the column "carrier"
airline_largest$carrier = factor(airline_largest$carrier)
#  Now we have:
# carrier: Factor w/ 4 levels "B6","DL","EV",..: 4 1 4 1 1 4 1 4 1 4 ...

# Plotting the behaviour of the number of flights per day divided by company
ggplot(airline_largest, aes(x=data, y=sum, color = levels(carrier)[carrier])) + 
    geom_point() +
    labs(title="Minimum delay of departure per aeroport per week", color = "Top companies") +
    xlab("Increasing day of the year") +
    ylab("Minimum delay of the day") +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("B6" = "orange", "DL"="purple", "EV"="blue", "UA"="green"))
